{"id":"Q11705","names":{"en":"Rashidun Caliphate","tr":"Râşidûn Halifeleri","ar":"al-Khulafā' al-Rāshidūn"},"country":["BH","EG","IQ","IR","PS","SA","SY","YE"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":632,"extinct":661},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"1","atlas_name_en_original":"The Rightly-Guided or 'Patriarchal' or 'Orthodox' Caliphs","parent_tribe":"Quraysh","ethnic_origin":"Arap","capital":"Medine (Medina); Kûfe (Kūfa) (Ali döneminde)","region_primary":"Hicaz - Medine (Medina)","regions_all":"Hicaz; Suriye; Filistin; Mısır; Irak; İran; Bahreyn; Umman; Yemen","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":"Hz. Muhammed (Peygamber dönemi)","successor":"Emevî Halifeleri","government_type":"Hilafet","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Rashidun Caliphate represents the founding political order of the Islamic community after Prophet Muhammad's death, dismantling the Sasanian Empire entirely and expelling Byzantium from Syria and Egypt within three decades. Abu Bakr secured Arabian unity through the Ridda Wars, while Umar transformed the conquests into a systematic state apparatus. Uthman standardized the Quranic text, but the civil strife (fitna) under Ali created the defining political fracture in Islamic history.","importance_level":"Yüksek","capital_lat":"24.47","capital_lon":"39.61","century_start":7,"century_end":7}}
{"id":"Q190375","names":{"en":"Mamluk Sultanate","tr":"Memlûkler","ar":"al-Mamālīk"},"country":["EG","IQ","PS","SA","SY"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1250,"extinct":1517},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"31","atlas_name_en_original":"The Mamlūks","parent_tribe":"Kıpçak Türkleri (Bahrî); Çerkesler (Burcî)","ethnic_origin":"Türk (Bahrî) / Çerkes (Burcî)","capital":"Kahire","region_primary":"Mısır ve Suriye","regions_all":"Mısır; Suriye; Filistin; Hicaz; Kuzey Irak kısmen; Kilikya; Nübya; Kıbrıs (haraçgüzar)","geographic_zone":"Mısır/Şam","predecessor":"Eyyûbîler","successor":"Osmanlı İmparatorluğu (Sultan Selim I)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":"Sünnî","narrative_en":"The Mamluks were a dynasty founded by slave-origin military elites that halted the Mongol invasion at Ayn Jalut and completely expelled the Crusaders from Syria. Throughout the Bahri and Burji periods, they positioned Egypt and Syria as the political and cultural center of the Islamic world, developing a unique system where succession passed not from father to son but to the strongest commander.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"30.04","capital_lon":"31.24","century_start":13,"century_end":16}}
{"id":"Q322895","names":{"en":"Tulunid dynasty","tr":"Tolunoğulları","ar":"al-Tūlūniyyūn"},"country":["EG","IQ","PS","SY"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":868,"extinct":905},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"25","atlas_name_en_original":"The Tūlūnids","parent_tribe":"Türk askerî ailesi (Buhara kökenli)","ethnic_origin":"Türk","capital":"Fustat (Eski Kahire) / al-Qatā'i'","region_primary":"Mısır ve Suriye","regions_all":"Mısır; Filistin; Suriye; Kuzey Mezopotamya (Cezire)","geographic_zone":"Mısır/Şam","predecessor":"Abbâsî valileri","successor":"Abbâsî doğrudan yönetimi (30 yıl)","government_type":"Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Tulunids were the first local dynasty to achieve de facto independence from the Abbasids in Egypt and Syria. The Ibn Tulun Mosque, built by Ahmad ibn Tulun of Turkic origin, still stands in Cairo as one of the oldest and best-preserved examples of Islamic architecture.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"30.04","capital_lon":"31.24","century_start":9,"century_end":10}}
{"id":"Q659375","names":{"en":"Ikhshidid dynasty","tr":"İhşîdîler","ar":"al-Ikhshīdiyyūn"},"country":["EG","PS","SY"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":935,"extinct":969},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"26","atlas_name_en_original":"The Ikhshīdids","parent_tribe":"Türk askerî ailesi (Fergana/Soğd kökenli)","ethnic_origin":"Türk","capital":"Fustat","region_primary":"Mısır ve Güney Suriye","regions_all":"Mısır; Güney Suriye; Filistin","geographic_zone":"Mısır/Şam","predecessor":"Abbâsî valileri","successor":"Fâtımîler (general Cevher'in fethi)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Ikhshidids were the second Turkic dynasty to rule Egypt after the Tulunids. The de facto regency of Kafur, a Nubian eunuch slave, stands as a remarkable example of social mobility in Islamic history; Egypt experienced a brief cultural flourishing under his patronage of the poet al-Mutanabbi.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"30.01","capital_lon":"31.23","century_start":10,"century_end":10}}
